The '''''dégradation nationale''''' ("National stripping of rank") was a sentence introduced in France after the [[Military history of France during World War II#Liberation of France|Liberation]]. It was applied during the ''[[épuration légale]]'' ("legal purge") which followed the fall of the [[Vichy France|Vichy regime]].<ref name=K90>{{cite book |last= Kritz |first=Neil J.  |date=1995 |title=Transitional Justice: How Emerging Democracies Reckon With Former Regimes |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A2c9E7TZXhEC  |location= |publisher=US Institute of Peace Press |page=90 |isbn=9781878379443 }}</ref>

The ''dégradation nationale'' was one of the sentences available to the ''[[Cour de justice|Cours de justice]]''. It was meant to punish offences of ''[[Indignité nationale]]''.

Individuals sentenced to the ''dégradation nationale'' lost their political, civil and professional rights. They effectively became [[second-class citizen]]s.

